SUBJECT: Functional Specifications
1. Indroduction
The specific document describes the solution in summary for subscription payments via JCCgateway and the REST APO specifications that can be used for the specific solution.
2. Solution Key Points
₣
F
. Merchant will be able to use the Redirect HTTP Post method to register a card and generate a token. This page can be customized with the colours and the logo of the merchant. Responsive version is also available.
. Merchant may then use this token to initiate one or more subscriptions using an API call
· Merchant should be also able to manage a subscription (update, cancel) to update in bulk the amount for multiple subscriptions.
· Option to retrieve transactions and subscriptions based on specific filters are also available using REST APIS ₣
. JCCgateway should handle the initiation of the payment based on the parameters that were defined by the merchant in the initiation API call. Therefore, JCC gateway should initiate the future payments for a specific subscription. In case of a specific payment was not approved, JCCgateway will need to try again as per the retry policy of the specific outlet. ₣
₣
· JCCgateway will inform the merchant using an API call for the status (approved or rejected) of each recurring transaction. Merchant will need to provide an HTTPS url for the specific need.
· Scheduled pending payments will be executed at a specific time daily except the failed transactions that will be executed based on their retry parameters
. Merchant should be able to define at the outlet level the interval in hours between the retries. JCCgateway will try up to 5 times for each transaction. Subscription will be cancelled if the 5th retry fails and the merchant should be notified using the proper API call. The cancellation reason should be FailedRetries.
₣
. Transactions will not be initiated if token is expired or if token was deactivated on purpose by the merchant. In this case subscription should be marked as Cancelled and the cancellation reason should be ExpiredToken or InactiveToken.
. The Merchant Order id of the 1st transaction (once-off OR subscription) will be the one that was sent by the merchant with the init call. The merchant Order id of all future transactions will be as below:
MerOrderId+_+NumberofPayment (padded with 0 to a total length of 5 digits)+_+Date (ddmmyyyy) +_+Time (hhmm) Sample: MerOrderId_00003_03112020_1321
. Merchant will be able to Capture, Reverse or Refund a transaction either via the JCCgateway merchant portal or via existing SOAP APIS.
. CaptureFlag: for the first transaction the value that was sent by the merchant in the API call will be used. For the recurring, transactions will be captured automatically.

APPENDIX A - Authentication mechanism
Authentication mechanism (using HMAC Signature)
The specific section describes the mechanism that it must be used for the specific API call.
It is a mechanism for calculating a message authentication code using a hash function in combination with a shared secret key between the two parties involved in sending and receiving the data (Front- end client and Back-end HTTP service). The main use for HMAC is to verify the integrity, authenticity, and the identity of the message sender.
The server (JCC) provides the client (Merchant) with a public APP Id and a shared secret key (API Key - shared only between the server and the client).
For Inbound calls (Merchant to JCC): the client should build a string by combining all the data that will be sent and the server must generate the same authentication value and compare the two in order to verify the call.
For Outbound calls (JCC to Merchant): the merchant is acting as a server and JCC as a client, although the public APP Id and shared secret key will be provided by JCC. At this case client (JCC) will build a string and sent it to server (Merchant) and the server must generate the same authentication value by the data provider from the client's string and verify the call.
This string contains the following parameters:
· APP Id
· HTTP method
· Request URI
· Request timestamp
· Nonce
· Base64 string representation of the request content.
Signature Generation
· APPId - server will provide this key to the client.
· HTTP method - POST or GET, capital letters.
· Request URI - full URL, lowercase and URL encoded. Example: https%3a%2f%2f192.168.209.17%2fapi%2faccount%2fregisteruser%2f
· Request timestamp - example: 1524651875
. Nonce - any alphanumeric character
· Request Content - Hashed using SHA256 and then converted to based64string.

System. Web.HttpUtility.UrlEncode(request.RequestUri.AbsoluteUri.ToLower()); string requestHttpMethod = request.Method.Method;
//Calculate UNIX time DateTime epochStart = new DateTime(1970, 01, 01, 0, 0, 0, 0, DateTimeKind.Utc); TimeSpan timeSpan = DateTime.UtcNow - epochStart; string requestTimeStamp = Convert.ToUInt64(timeSpan.TotalSeconds).ToString();
//create random nonce for each request string nonce = Guid.NewGuid().ToString("N"); //Checking if the request contains body, usually will be null with HTTP GET and DELETE if (request.Content != null) { byte[] content = await request.Content.ReadAsByteArrayAsync(); SHA256 sha256 = SHA256.Create(); //Hashing the request body, any change in request body will result in different hash, we'll incure message integrity byte[] requestContentHash = sha256.ComputeHash(content); requestContentBase64String = Convert.ToBase64String(requestContentHash); }
//Creating the raw signature string string signatureRawData = String.Format("{0} {1}{2}{3}{4}{5}",APPId, requestHttpMethod, requestUri, requestTimeStamp, nonce, requestContentBase64String);
var secretKeyByteArray = Convert.FromBase64String(APIKey); byte[] signature = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(signatureRawData); using (HMACSHA256 hmac = new HMACSHA256(secretKeyByteArray)) { byte[] signatureBytes = hmac.ComputeHash(signature); string requestSignatureBase64String = Convert.ToBase64String(signatureBytes); //Setting the values in the Authorization header using custom scheme (amx) request.Headers.Authorization = new AuthenticationHeader Value("amx", string.Format("{0}:{1}:{2}:{3}",APPId, requestSignatureBase64String, nonce, requestTimeStamp)); }

The specific section describes the mechanism that it must be used for the specific API call.

It is a mechanism for calculating a message authentication code using a hash function in combination with a shared secret key between the two parties involved in sending and receiving the data (Front- end client and Back-end HTTP service). The main use for HMAC is to verify the integrity, authenticity, and the identity of the message sender.
The server (JCC) provides the client (Merchant) with a public APP Id and a shared secret key (API Key - shared only between the server and the client).

For Inbound calls (Merchant to JCC): the client should build a string by combining all the data that will be sent and the server must generate the same authentication value and compare the two in order to verify the call.

For Outbound calls (JCC to Merchant): the merchant is acting as a server and JCC as a client, although the public APP Id and shared secret key will be provided by JCC. At this case client (JCC) will build a string and sent it to server (Merchant) and the server must generate the same authentication value by the data provider from the client's string and verify the call.
This string contains the following parameters:
· Base64 string representation of the request content.
· APPId - server will provide this key to the client.
· HTTP method - POST or GET, capital letters.
· Request URI - full URL, lowercase and URL encoded. Example: https%3a%2f%2f192.168.209.17%2fapi%2faccount%2fregisteruser%2f
· Request Content - Hashed using SHA256 and then converted to based64string.
Example of header generation in C#

//Calculate UNIX time DateTime epochStart = new DateTime(1970, 01, 01, 0, 0, 0, 0, DateTimeKind.Utc); TimeSpan timeSpan = DateTime.UtcNow - epochStart; string requestTimeStamp = Convert.ToUInt64(timeSpan.TotalSeconds).ToString();

//create random nonce for each request string nonce = Guid.NewGuid().ToString("N"); //Checking if the request contains body, usually will be null with HTTP GET and DELETE if (request.Content != null) { byte[] content = await request.Content.ReadAsByteArrayAsync(); SHA256 sha256 = SHA256.Create(); //Hashing the request body, any change in request body will result in different hash, we'll incure message integrity byte[] requestContentHash = sha256.ComputeHash(content); requestContentBase64String = Convert.ToBase64String(requestContentHash); }
//Creating the raw signature string string signatureRawData = String.Format("{0} {1}{2}{3}{4}{5}",APPId, requestHttpMethod, requestUri, requestTimeStamp, nonce, requestContentBase64String);

var secretKeyByteArray = Convert.FromBase64String(APIKey); byte[] signature = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(signatureRawData); using (HMACSHA256 hmac = new HMACSHA256(secretKeyByteArray)) { byte[] signatureBytes = hmac.ComputeHash(signature); string requestSignatureBase64String = Convert.ToBase64String(signatureBytes); //Setting the values in the Authorization header using custom scheme (amx) request.Headers.Authorization = new AuthenticationHeader Value("amx", string.Format("{0}:{1}:{2}:{3}",APPId, requestSignatureBase64String, nonce, requestTimeStamp)); }
